Do you think that a chart provides a sense of the perfect entry point? It doesnt. And rarely see anyone talking about the size of postions Nor do fundamentals. With a market structure that increasingly exaggerates short term swings and momentum this is the business I have chosen.
And I update frequently on my sizing of positions - its an understated straegy/craft imho.

Again, there are many ways to approach risk taking. Some use charts. I use fundies and develop sense of intrinsic value vs. share price. If share price is less than intrinsic value I go long and the deeper it gets I go longer. Conversely same on the short side. Seems to me

that there is little discussion ever on sizing. I spend alot of time discussing size in my positions and the benefits (from a risk control standpoint) of averaging in in an uncertain market dominated by machines and algos.
As you know I write for Jim and not for Jack! @realmoney contains the subtleties and particulars of my approach to investing and trading. @jimcramer
Read @realmoney on how I scale into positions. I write often about this I my blog.

You know I love you Tim but I disagree. Here is why. I always start small in my positions, long or short and average in. Unlike many, especially in a market that is structured to exaggerate s term moves (quants, etfs) I dont know ideal entry point.
